Here's a JavaScript function that takes an array of 5 numbers as input, checks if any of them are prime numbers, and prints the prime numbers to the console using an optimized `isPrime` function:

```javascript
function isPrime(num) {
  if (num <= 1) return false;
  if (num <= 3) return true;
  if (num % 2 === 0 || num % 3 === 0) return false;

  let i = 5;
  while (i * i <= num) {
    if (num % i === 0 || num % (i + 2) === 0) return false;
    i += 6;
  }

  return true;
}

function checkForPrimes(numbers) {
  if (numbers.length !== 5) {
    console.error('Please provide an array with exactly 5 numbers.');
    return;
  }

  for (let number of numbers) {
    if (isPrime(number)) {
      console.log(number);
    }
  }
}

// Example usage:
const numbersArray = [10, 17, 23, 45, 53];
checkForPrimes(numbersArray);
```

The `isPrime` function checks if a given number is prime using an optimized algorithm. It skips even numbers (except 2) and multiples of 3 to reduce the number of checks needed. 

The `checkForPrimes` function first verifies if the input array has exactly 5 numbers. If not, it prints an error message and returns. Otherwise, it iterates over the array and calls `isPrime` for each number. If a prime number is found, it's printed to the console using `console.log`.

The example usage at the bottom shows how to call the function with an array of 5 numbers. When running this code, the prime numbers (17, 23, and 53) from the `numbersArray` will be printed to the console.

Here's an example of HTML code that imitates a fake chatbot using a modal, displaying a chat history with 4 messages, 2 from the AI chatbot and 2 from the human user:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
