            float: right;
            font-size: 28px;
            font-weight: bold;
        }

        .close:hover,
        .close:focus {
            color: black;
            text-decoration: none;
            cursor: pointer;
        }

        /* Chat message styles */
        .chat-message {
            display: flex;
            align-items: baseline;
            margin-bottom: 10px;
        }

        .chat-message .sender {
            font-weight: bold;
        }

        .chat-message .message {
            padding: 5px 10px;
            border-radius: 5px;
            max-width: 75%;
            word-wrap: break-word;
        }

        .bot-message {
            justify-content: flex-end;
            background-color: #b0e0e6;
        }

        .human-message {
            justify-content: flex-start;
            background-color: #f0e68c;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <button id="openModal">View Chat History</button>

    <div id="myModal" class="modal">
        <div class="modal-content">
            <span class="close">&times;</span>
            <div class="chat-message">
                <span class="sender">Human:</span>
                <div class="human-message message">Hi there, how are you?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="chat-message">
                <span class="sender">AI Chatbot:</span>
                <div class="bot-message message">I'm great, thank you! How can I help you today?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="chat-message">
                <span class="sender">Human:</span>
                <div class="human-message message">Can you tell me about the weather today?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="chat-message">
                <span class="sender">AI Chatbot:</span>
                <div class="bot-message message">Sure, it's sunny with a high of 75°F. Don't forget your sunglasses!</div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <script>
        // Function to open and close the modal
        document.getElementById("openModal").addEventListener("click", function() {
            document.getElementById("myModal").style.display = "block";
        });

        var closeBtn = document.getElementsByClassName("close")[0];
        closeBtn.addEventListener("click", function() {
            document.getElementById("myModal").style.display = "none";
        });

        window.addEventListener("click", function(event) {
            if (event.target == document.getElementById("myModal")) {
                document.getElementById("myModal").style.display = "none";
            }
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

This code creates a simple modal chat history with four messages. When you click the "View Chat History" button, the modal will appear, and when you click on the "x" or outside the modal, it will close. The chat messages are styled differently for the AI chatbot and the human user.

In TypeScript, you can use type assertions to inform the type system that you are confident the value will have a more specific type than what the compiler can infer. Type assertions effectively tell TypeScript, "Trust me, I know what I'm doing." There are two main syntaxes for type assertions:

1. Using the `as` keyword:
```typescript
let value: string | number; // value could be a string or a number

// But you know in practice it's a string
let knownString = value as string;

// Now TypeScript treats knownString as a string
knownString.toUpperCase();
```
1. Using angle brackets (`<>`):
```typescript
let value: string | number;

// You're certain it's a string
let knownString = <string>value;

// Now you can treat knownString as a string
knownString.toUpperCase();
```
Keep in mind that type assertions bypass TypeScript's type checking, so if you are incorrect, you could introduce runtime errors. It's important to use type assertions with caution and only when you're absolutely sure about the type of the value.

Another safer approach to narrowing the type based on runtime information is to use **type guards**. Type guards allow you to check the type at runtime and inform the type system about the narrowed type:

```typescript
let value: string | number;

// Check if value is a string
if (typeof value === 'string') {
  // Inside this block, TypeScript knows value is a string
  const knownString = value;
  knownString.toUpperCase();
} else {
  // TypeScript knows value is a number here
}
```
In this example, the `typeof` check is a type guard that narrows the type of `value` within the corresponding `if` block. This way, you benefit from TypeScript's type checking while still conveying your knowledge about the actual type of the value.

